[SDG-VOX]: Say 'system command' (or 'cmd', 'computer', 'i cast', or 'highcast') followed by your command to activate voice control. Customize wake words in the Settings dialog of the config GUI.
[SDG-VOX]: You can say 'open firefox' to launch apps, 'volume up' to adjust audio, 'search for cats' to search the web, or 'type hello world' to type text. Natural filler words like 'the' and 'please' are ignored.
[SDG-VOX]: Ensure your microphone is working by running 'pactl info' and checking the Default Source. SDG-VOX captures audio via GStreamer and PipeWire with automatic voice activity detection.
[SDG-VOX]: After your first command, you have a 3-second grace period to speak another without repeating the wake word. Look for the HUD overlay confirmation.
[SDG-VOX]: Use 'administrator' before any command to run it with sudo, or say 'background' after a command to run it in the background. Other modifiers: 'silent' (suppress output) and 'detach' (detach from terminal).
[SDG-VOX]: Run 'sdgvox config' to open the GTK configuration editor with a visual flowchart of your command graph. Drag to connect nodes and edit commands visually.
[SDG-VOX]: The daemon shows a transparent HUD overlay with real-time transcriptions at the top of your screen. Use 'sdgvox daemon --headless' to run without it.
[SDG-VOX]: Say 'cancel' at any time to abort the current command and exit the 3-second grace period. The overlay will show 'Cancelled'.
[SDG-VOX]: Commands with text capture (like 'search for' and 'type') automatically capture everything you say after the keyword. Say 'search for cute cats' and it searches for exactly that.
[SDG-VOX]: The daemon hot-reloads config changes every ~1 second. Edit your command graph in the GUI, save, and your next voice command will use the new graph — no restart needed.
